              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Retirement &amp; pensions FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How much do I need to retire?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    A common starting point is to target
                    <strong>70–80% of your pre-retirement income</strong>, but
                    this can vary widely. If you will be mortgage-free, have no
                    dependants, and expect modest spending, you may need less.
                    If you plan to travel extensively or support family members,
                    you may need more. Use the calculator to compare your target
                    with your projected income and adjust until the plan feels
                    realistic.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What counts as retirement income in this planner?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The planner includes:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mt-1">
                      <li>Employer pensions (DB or DC plans).</li>
                      <li>
                        Government benefits (CPP/QPP, OAS, Social Security,
                        state pensions, etc.).
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Other recurring income such as rental income, annuities,
                        or part-time work.
                      </li>
                      <li>Withdrawals from your savings and investments.</li>
                    </ul>
                    One-time lump sums or inheritances are not modeled
                    separately, but you can add them to your
                    <strong>current savings</strong> or adjust contributions to
                    approximate their effect.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What investment return and inflation assumptions should I
                    use?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    There is no single “correct” assumption. Historically,
                    diversified stock portfolios have returned more than bonds
                    or cash, but future returns may be lower. Many planners use:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mt-1">
                      <li>
                        <strong>4–6% nominal return</strong> with
                        <strong>2–3% inflation</strong>, or
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <strong>3–4% real return</strong> (after inflation).
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    If you want a more conservative plan, lower the return or
                    increase the inflation assumption. You can also run multiple
                    scenarios (optimistic, base case, conservative) to see a
                    range of outcomes.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is a safe withdrawal rate from my savings?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The well-known <strong>4% rule</strong> suggests that
                    withdrawing 4% of your initial portfolio value in the first
                    year of retirement and adjusting for inflation each year has
                    historically worked for many 30-year retirements in U.S.
                    data. However:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mt-1">
                      <li>It is based on past returns that may not repeat.</li>
                      <li>It assumes a specific asset mix and fee level.</li>
                      <li>
                        It does not adapt withdrawals to market conditions.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    Use the implied withdrawal rate shown in the results as a
                    guide, not a guarantee. If your rate is much higher than
                    4–5%, consider saving more, working longer, or lowering your
                    target spending.
                  </div>
                </details>

                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can this calculator replace professional financial advice?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
